## LICENSE FLOW (pages/licenses/)

### LicenseHub.jsx (`/reallives/licenses`)
- Displays 4 cards, one per user type: School, University, Homeschooler, Gamer
- Each card is a `<LicenseCard />` component from `components/common/LicenseCard/`
- Each card links to its detail page: `/reallives/licenses/<type>`
- Content (card title, description, icon) comes from `src/content/licenses.js`
- No sub-site navbar вЂ” this page is inside `LandingLayout`

### License Detail Pages (`/reallives/licenses/school` etc.)
Each of the 4 license detail pages (`SchoolLicense.jsx`, `UniversityLicense.jsx`, etc.) follows the same structure:
- Shows the license tiers available for that user type (e.g. Basic, Standard, Premium)
- Each tier is a `<LicenseTierCard />` component showing the tier name, price, and benefits list
- Two CTAs at the bottom (or per-tier if appropriate):

```jsx
{/* CTA 1 вЂ” Visit the sub-site */}
<Link to="/reallives/school">Visit Website</Link>

{/* CTA 2 вЂ” Go to registration form */}
<Link to="/reallives/register/school">Buy License</Link>
```

- All license content (tier names, prices, benefits) lives in `src/content/licenses.js` вЂ” not hardcoded in JSX

### licenses.js content structure
```js
// src/content/licenses.js
export const licensesContent = {
  school: {
    title: "School License",
    description: "...",
    icon: "...",
    tiers: [
      {
        id: "school-basic",
        name: "Basic",
        price: "...",
        benefits: ["...", "...", "..."],
      },
      {
        id: "school-standard",
        name: "Standard",
        price: "...",
        benefits: ["...", "...", "..."],
      },
    ],
    visitPath: "/reallives/school",
    registerPath: "/reallives/register/school",
  },
  university: { ... },
  homeschooler: { ... },
  gamer: { ... },
};
```

License detail pages import from this file directly (not via `useSiteContent` вЂ” these pages are not inside a sub-site context):
```jsx
import { licensesContent } from '@content/licenses';
const content = licensesContent['school'];
```

### Registration Pages (`/reallives/register/<type>`)
- One page per user type, each in `pages/register/`
- These are form pages вЂ” render the registration form for that user type
- If the registration is an external URL (e.g. a third-party form), use `window.location.href` or a plain `<a href target="_blank">` вЂ” do NOT use React Router `<Link>` for external destinations
- If it is an internal form, build it as a controlled React form with state

---

## DYNAMIC FOOTER (components/common/Footer/)

The sub-site `Footer` component is dynamic. It does not have a hardcoded list of links. Instead, it reads the current sub-site's navigation links from the content file and renders them automatically.

### How it works

Each content file exports a `navLinks` array:
```js
// src/content/school.js
export const schoolContent = {
  navLinks: [
    { label: "Home",       path: "/reallives/school" },
    { label: "About Us",   path: "/reallives/school/about" },
    { label: "Features",   path: "/reallives/school/features" },
    { label: "Contact",    path: "/reallives/school/contact" },
    // ... all pages that appear in this sub-site's navbar
  ],
  // ... rest of content
};
```

The `Footer` component reads this via `useSiteContent()`:
```jsx
import { useSiteContent } from '@hooks/useSiteContent';

export default function Footer() {
  const { navLinks, footer } = useSiteContent();

  return (
    <footer className={styles.footer}>
      <nav className={styles.linkGrid}>
        {navLinks.map(link => (
          <Link key={link.path} to={link.path} className={styles.link}>
            {link.label}
          </Link>
        ))}
      </nav>
      {/* Other footer content (tagline, social links, copyright) */}
    </footer>
  );
}
```

This means:
- Adding a new page to the school sub-site = add it to `navLinks` in `school.js` вЂ” the footer updates automatically
- The Navbar also reads from the same `navLinks` array, so both stay in sync from a single source of truth
- Never maintain a separate link list for the footer

### LandingFooter (components/landing/LandingFooter/)
- Completely separate from the sub-site `Footer`
- Has its own unique About blurb and Contact Us information for the landing page
- Its content lives in a dedicated `src/content/landing.js` file (not in any sub-site content file)
- It does NOT render sub-site nav links вЂ” it has its own set of links relevant to the landing context only
- Example content structure:
```js
// src/content/landing.js
export const landingContent = {
  footer: {
    about: "RealLives is a simulation game that...",
    contact: {
      email: "...",
      address: "...",
    },
    links: [
      { label: "About", path: "/reallives/about" },   // landing-level pages if any
      { label: "Contact", path: "/reallives/contact" },
    ],
  },
};
```

