### ThemeContext.jsx
Implement exactly as follows:

```jsx
import { createContext, useContext, useState, useEffect } from 'react';

const ThemeContext = createContext();

export function ThemeProvider({ children }) {
  const [theme, setTheme] = useState(
    () => localStorage.getItem('rl-theme') || 'light'
  );

  useEffect(() => {
    document.documentElement.setAttribute('data-theme', theme);
    localStorage.setItem('rl-theme', theme);
  }, [theme]);

  const toggleTheme = () =>
    setTheme(prev => (prev === 'light' ? 'dark' : 'light'));

  return (
    <ThemeContext.Provider value={{ theme, toggleTheme }}>
      {children}
    </ThemeContext.Provider>
  );
}

export function useTheme() {
  return useContext(ThemeContext);
}
```

Key rules:
- On app load, reads from `localStorage` first. If nothing is stored, defaults to `'light'`
- On every theme change, writes to `localStorage` and updates `data-theme` on `<html>`
- This means if a user picks dark mode and refreshes, dark mode persists automatically

### global.css (theming)
All color values must use CSS custom properties. Never hardcode colors in component CSS. Define all tokens here:

```css
:root {
  --color-bg-primary: #ffffff;
  --color-bg-secondary: #f5f5f5;
  --color-text-primary: #111111;
  --color-text-secondary: #555555;
  --color-accent: #your-brand-color;
  --color-border: #dddddd;
  --color-card-bg: #ffffff;

  --font-primary: 'Your Font', sans-serif;
  --font-size-base: 16px;
  --spacing-sm: 8px;
  --spacing-md: 16px;
  --spacing-lg: 32px;
  --border-radius: 8px;
  --transition-speed: 0.2s;
}

[data-theme="dark"] {
  --color-bg-primary: #1a1a1a;
  --color-bg-secondary: #252525;
  --color-text-primary: #eeeeee;
  --color-text-secondary: #aaaaaa;
  --color-accent: #your-brand-color-dark-variant;
  --color-border: #333333;
  --color-card-bg: #252525;
}
```

Every component uses `var(--color-bg-primary)` etc. вЂ” never a raw hex. Switching the theme attribute flips the entire site automatically.

---

## CSS MODULES RULES

- Every component has its own `.module.css` file in the same folder
- Import it as `import styles from './ComponentName.module.css'`
- Apply classes as `className={styles.wrapper}` etc.
- Never use global class names in component files (no `className="navbar"`)
- For conditional classes, use template literals: `` className={`${styles.btn} ${isActive ? styles.active : ''}`} ``
- For combining with a utility: use the `clsx` library if needed

---

## CONTENT SEPARATION PATTERN

Since school, university, and homeschooler share 90% of their components but have different content, use a content config file per sub-site. This is the most important reusability pattern in the whole project.

### Example: src/content/school.js
```js
export const schoolContent = {
  hero: {
    title: "RealLives for Schools",
    subtitle: "...",
    ctaText: "Get Started",
  },
  features: [
    { id: 1, title: "...", description: "...", icon: "..." },
    // ...
  ],
  testimonials: [...],
  about: {
    heading: "About Our School Program",
    body: "...",
  },
  // ... all text content for this sub-site
};
```

### useSiteContent.js hook
```js
import { useContext } from 'react';
import SiteContext from '../context/SiteContext';
import { schoolContent } from '../content/school';
import { universityContent } from '../content/university';
import { homeschoolerContent } from '../content/homeschooler';
import { gamerContent } from '../content/gamer';

const contentMap = {
  school: schoolContent,
  university: universityContent,
  homeschooler: homeschoolerContent,
  gamer: gamerContent,
};

export function useSiteContent() {
  const { siteKey } = useContext(SiteContext);
  return contentMap[siteKey] || {};
}
```

Shared components like `<HeroSection />` call `useSiteContent()` to get their text. Changing content for university = edit `university.js`. No JSX files need to change.

---

## COMPONENT RULES

### One component = one folder
```
components/common/Navbar/
в”њв”Ђв”Ђ Navbar.jsx
в””в”Ђв”Ђ Navbar.module.css
```
Never put component CSS in a shared stylesheet. Never put two components in the same file.

### Component props design
- Pass only what the component needs вЂ” no "god objects"
- Use `siteKey` context (via `useSiteContent`) for content variation, not props drilling
- For truly static content (e.g. social links in footer that are the same everywhere), it's fine to hardcode inside the component

### Shared components (common/)
These are components used across two or more sub-sites or pages:
- `Navbar` вЂ” adapts nav links based on `navLinks` from `useSiteContent()`
- `Footer` вЂ” dynamic, reads `navLinks` from `useSiteContent()` to render all page links automatically
- `AboutUs` вЂ” renders content from `useSiteContent().about`
- `ContactUs`
- `Carousel` вЂ” accepts `slides` as a prop (array of image/text objects)
- `HeroSection`
- `FeatureCard`
- `TestimonialCard`
- `PageHeader`
- `CTABanner`
- `LicenseCard` вЂ” used in `LicenseHub.jsx` to show each user-type option
- `LicenseTierCard` вЂ” used in each license detail page to show a single tier with benefits

### Landing-specific components (landing/)
- `LandingFooter` вЂ” unique footer only for the landing page, has its own About and Contact content

When you create a new component that's used in more than one sub-site, always put it in `common/`. Landing-specific components (only ever appear on `/reallives` and its pre-entry pages) go in `landing/`.

---

## 404 PAGE (NotFound.jsx)

Must include:
- A clear "Page Not Found" heading
- The URL that was attempted (use `useLocation()` from React Router to display it)
- A prominent "Go to Home" button that links to `"/"`
- Styled consistently with the rest of the site (uses theme variables, is mobile responsive)
- The cat is optional but encouraged (the team mentioned it вЂ” add a small illustration or emoji cat if you like)

---

## MOBILE RESPONSIVENESS

Every component must be responsive. Rules:
- Use CSS Grid and Flexbox вЂ” no fixed pixel widths on layout containers
- Breakpoints defined as CSS custom properties or media queries in each module.css:
  ```css
  /* Mobile first */
  .grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr; gap: var(--spacing-md); }

  @media (min-width: 768px) {
    .grid { grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr); }
  }

  @media (min-width: 1024px) {
    .grid { grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr); }
  }
  ```
- Navbar must have a hamburger menu on mobile (implement a `menuOpen` state in Navbar.jsx)
- All font sizes in `rem`, not `px`
- All images: `max-width: 100%; height: auto`
- Touch targets (buttons, links) minimum 44px tall

---

## VITE SETUP

Initialize the project with:
```bash
npm create vite@latest reallives -- --template react
cd reallives
npm install
npm install react-router-dom
```

Optional but recommended:
```bash
npm install clsx        # for conditional classNames
```

In `vite.config.js`, set the base path if the site is hosted at a subdirectory. If it's at the root domain, the default is fine.

Configure path aliases for cleaner imports:
```js
// vite.config.js
import { defineConfig } from 'vite';
import react from '@vitejs/plugin-react';
import path from 'path';

export default defineConfig({
  plugins: [react()],
  resolve: {
    alias: {
      '@': path.resolve(__dirname, './src'),
      '@components': path.resolve(__dirname, './src/components'),
      '@pages': path.resolve(__dirname, './src/pages'),
      '@content': path.resolve(__dirname, './src/content'),
      '@hooks': path.resolve(__dirname, './src/hooks'),
      '@context': path.resolve(__dirname, './src/context'),
    },
  },
});
```

This means imports look like `import Navbar from '@components/common/Navbar/Navbar'` instead of `'../../../components/common/Navbar/Navbar'`.

