## CONVERSION PROCESS вЂ” STEP BY STEP

Follow this order. Do not skip steps.

### Step 1 вЂ” Audit the original HTML
Before converting any page, list out:
- All sections/pages that exist in the navbar of each sub-site
- All license tiers and their benefits for each user type
- All repeating UI blocks (hero, cards, testimonials, license tiers, etc.)
- All images and assets that need to be moved to `src/assets/`
- All existing CSS classes that need to be replicated

### Step 2 вЂ” Scaffold the project
- Run Vite setup
- Create every folder in the structure above (even empty ones)
- Create `global.css` with all theme variables extracted from the original CSS
- Create `ThemeContext.jsx` and `SiteContext.jsx`
- Create `App.jsx` with all routes stubbed (pages can just return `<div>PageName</div>` at first)

### Step 3 вЂ” Build content files first (before any components)
This is the most important step for keeping the project maintainable:
1. Create `src/content/school.js` вЂ” include `navLinks` array with every page in the school navbar
2. Create `src/content/university.js` вЂ” same structure
3. Create `src/content/homeschooler.js` вЂ” same structure
4. Create `src/content/gamer.js` вЂ” same structure
5. Create `src/content/licenses.js` вЂ” all license tiers and benefits for all 4 user types
6. Create `src/content/landing.js` вЂ” landing page footer content (About, Contact, links)

The `navLinks` array in each content file is the single source of truth for both the Navbar and the Footer. Define it once here.

### Step 4 вЂ” Build common components
Start with the components used on the most pages:
1. `Navbar` (reads `navLinks` from `useSiteContent()`, includes dark mode toggle and mobile hamburger)
2. `Footer` (reads `navLinks` from `useSiteContent()`, renders them as links automatically)
3. `LandingFooter` (reads from `landing.js`, has unique About and Contact content)
4. `Carousel`
5. `HeroSection`
6. `AboutUs`, `ContactUs`
7. `FeatureCard`, `TestimonialCard`
8. `LicenseCard`, `LicenseTierCard`

Test each component in isolation before moving on.

### Step 5 вЂ” Build layouts
1. `RootLayout`
2. `LandingLayout` (wraps with `LandingFooter`)
3. `SubSiteLayout` (wires up `SiteContext`, wraps with `Navbar` + `Footer`)
4. `GamerLayout`

### Step 6 вЂ” Build pages in this order
1. `Portal.jsx`
2. `RealLivesLanding.jsx` (carousel + 4 entry cards + Buy License CTA + Login CTA)
3. `Login.jsx`
4. `LicenseHub.jsx` (4 user-type cards)
5. All 4 license detail pages (SchoolLicense, UniversityLicense, HomeschoolerLicense, GamerLicense)
6. All 4 registration pages
7. All school pages
8. All university pages (reuse school components, swap content via `useSiteContent`)
9. All homeschooler pages (same approach)
10. All gamer pages

### Step 7 вЂ” 404 page
Build `NotFound.jsx` last, once routing is confirmed working.

### Step 8 вЂ” QA checklist
Before considering any page done, verify:
- [ ] Dark mode works and persists on refresh
- [ ] Mobile layout is correct at 375px, 768px, 1024px widths
- [ ] No hardcoded colors in any component (all use CSS variables)
- [ ] No CSS class name conflicts (all using CSS Modules)
- [ ] All internal links use `<Link>` from React Router, not `<a href>`
- [ ] All images have `alt` attributes
- [ ] The 404 page appears for any unknown route
- [ ] Sub-site footer dynamically shows all navbar links for that sub-site
- [ ] Adding a link to `navLinks` in a content file makes it appear in both Navbar and Footer
- [ ] Landing page footer shows its own unique About and Contact вЂ” not sub-site content
- [ ] License detail pages link to the correct sub-site (`visitPath`) and registration form (`registerPath`)
- [ ] `component-map.md` is updated

---

## THINGS TO NEVER DO

- Never use `<a href>` for internal navigation вЂ” always `<Link to>` from React Router
- Never hardcode color values in component CSS вЂ” always `var(--color-*)`
- Never write global CSS inside a `.module.css` file
- Never put two components in one file
- Never put content (text, copy) inside JSX вЂ” it must come from a content file
- Never use inline styles for layout вЂ” use CSS Modules
- Never skip the mobile breakpoints
- Never create a new component without its own `.module.css` file
- Never maintain a separate link list in the Footer вЂ” it must read from `navLinks` in the content file
- Never use the sub-site `<Footer />` on the landing page, license pages, login, or register pages вЂ” those use `<LandingFooter />`
- Never use `<LandingFooter />` inside a sub-site layout вЂ” those use `<Footer />`
- Never hardcode license tier data or benefits in JSX вЂ” it must come from `licenses.js`
- Never duplicate `navLinks` вЂ” the same array must power both the Navbar and the Footer for each sub-site

---

## NOTES FOR CURSOR

- When Cursor asks "should I create this file?", the answer is yes вЂ” create the full folder structure upfront even if pages are empty stubs
- When converting a section from the original HTML, extract all text into the relevant `content/*.js` file before writing JSX
- When a component is used in more than one sub-site, it belongs in `components/common/`, not in a sub-site folder
- When unsure whether something is "common" or "sub-site specific", default to `common/` вЂ” it's easier to move out than to discover duplication later
- The gamer sub-site shares `AboutUs`, `ContactUs`, `Footer` and any other generic pages вЂ” do not duplicate these into `components/gamer/`
- CSS Modules automatically scope class names вЂ” you do not need to prefix classes with the component name (`.navbar__link` is unnecessary; `.link` is fine inside `Navbar.module.css`)
- The `navLinks` array in each content file is intentionally the single source of truth for both Navbar and Footer вЂ” if you find yourself writing link lists in two places, stop and fix it
- License detail pages are NOT inside a sub-site context, so they import from `licenses.js` directly rather than using `useSiteContent()`
- The two footer components (`Footer` and `LandingFooter`) are completely separate вЂ” do not try to make one component handle both cases with a prop flag